Consumes the `Weak<T>` and turns it into a raw pointer.

This converts the weak pointer into a raw pointer, while still preserving the ownership of one weak reference (the weak count is not modified by this operation). It can be turned back into the `Weak<T>` with [`from_raw`](about:blank/struct.Weak.html#method.from_raw "associated function std::rc::Weak::from_raw").

The same restrictions of accessing the target of the pointer as with [`as_ptr`](about:blank/struct.Weak.html#method.as_ptr "method std::rc::Weak::as_ptr") apply.

##### [Â§](#examples-4)Examples

```
use std::rc::{Rc, Weak};

let strong = Rc::new("hello".to_owned());
let weak = Rc::downgrade(&strong);
let raw = weak.into_raw();

assert_eq!(1, Rc::weak_count(&strong));
assert_eq!("hello", unsafe { &*raw });

drop(unsafe { Weak::from_raw(raw) });
assert_eq!(0, Rc::weak_count(&strong));
```

